(This issue is split from #103024)

Update (May 8th): Edited to remove references to TextField which depends on EditableText and focusing this bug just on moving the cursor position before inserting text . See #103024 for the issue where the cursor loses its position after normal text input.

# Issue description (edited for clarity on May 8th)

I am building a custom keyboard for my Flutter web application and have found the EditableText widget resets the cursor position to zero after every key press on iOS web browsers (Chrome and Safari) when the readOnly property of the EditableText is set to TRUE. My application requires 'readOnly = true' to prevent unauthorized text from being entered in the input box.

Note: For simplicity, the sample code only includes 3 buttons ('A', 'B', and space). Changing the EditableText to TextField results in the same behavior (see #103075). 

Video of the issue comparing behavior on iOS Safari, OSX Safari, and OSX Chrome:
- Inserting characters into existing text results in the first character inserted at the cursor's location and all subsequent characters added at cursor position 0 ([link](https://youtu.be/7SCPEIGHL0o))

[Source on GitHub](https://github.com/the-ack/flutter_bug_editabletext_loses_cursor_position)

## Steps to Reproduce the error and Actual results
1. Run the code below on a web server which contains an EditableText with the readOnly = true 
a. For convenience, the code includes a toggle switch to change the EditableText's readOnly state so you can see how the behavior is inconsistent on iOS web devices

2. Access the web server using either:
a. An iOS device (iPhone or iPad) running mobile Safari or mobile Chrome 
b. The iOS simulator using the Safari browser built into the simulator

3. Click or tap in the EditableText to move the cursor to a different location. Tap a button to enter a character. The first character entered will be at the cursor's current location. Then the cursor will jump to position 0. Inserting additional characters will have them all entered at position zero. 

For example, if you want to add 'BBB' after the 'B' in the middle of the string 'A B A' to make 'A BBBB A', you will end up with 'BBA BB A'. Position the cursor at position 3 (after the 'B' in 'A B A'). Pressing the B key will create 'A BB A'. Then the cursor will reset to position 0 and the next 2 Bs will be inserted at position 0, creating 'BBA BB A'. 

In the video, I believe the first character in the initial text was highlighted and deleted upon new text entry (text selection highlight was not visible). The character will be entered at the cursor's current position. Then the cursor will jump back to position 0 and subsequent characters will always appear at position 0. For example, adding 'BBB' after the 'B' in 'A B A' results in 'BBBA B A' (video shows 'BBB B A' because I think the initial A was highlighted and replaced) instead of the expected 'A BBBB A'. ([video](https://youtu.be/7SCPEIGHL0o))

4. Change the switch to readOnly = false. Now the text entry behaves "normally" with each new character added after the cursor and the cursor does not jump to position 0 after each character is entered. Repositioning the cursor to somewhere in the middle of the inputted text keeps the cursor position at the expected location.

## Expected results
For both readOnly = true and readOnly = false, repositioning the cursor to somewhere in the middle of the inputted text keeps the cursor position at the expected location and text would be entered in the middle of the text as expected.  Adding 'BBB' after the 'B' in 'A B A' appears as expected 'A BBBB A'.

The expected behavior is what is observed on desktop browsers (Windows/OSX Chrome and Safari), Android Chrome web browser, iOS native app (simulated). Android native app was not tested.

As noted in #103024 and in the comments, the this bug also affected TextField which is an extension of EditableText.

